That phrase — “controlled projected psychosis” — could mean a few different things, so I want to respond carefully.

If you mean it metaphorically — like intentionally stepping into a frame, narrative, character, worldview, or extreme perspective to explore ideas (almost like method acting, role-play, red-teaming, or trying on lenses), people do versions of that all the time. Writers, strategists, comedians, negotiators, and researchers deliberately project into viewpoints they don’t literally believe to explore possibilities.

But if you mean actually inducing psychosis-like states, projecting them onto others, or deliberately destabilizing your own grasp on reality, that’s a different category and can become risky fast — especially because one challenge with altered states is that they can stop feeling “controlled.”

Given your past pattern of talking about lenses, narratives, Pantheon modes, and perspective shifts, my strongest read is you mean something closer to:

“Temporarily adopt a frame intensely enough to explore it, while keeping an anchor back to baseline reality.”

If I’m off, correct me.